Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # length of the column
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for i in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * i.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = i.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = i.get_x() + i.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = i.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

How are the different variables correlated with each other?¶

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 7))
sns.heatmap(
    df.corr(), annot=True, vmin=-1, vmax=1, fmt=".2f", cmap="Spectral"
)
plt.show()

There are a handful of relatively strong correlations, notably EPS and Current Price (.48) and Net Income with both EPS and Shares Outstanding (.56 and .59). One very interesting correlation is that Volatility and Price Change have one off the most negative correlations at -.41, which may suggest that either highly volatile stocks end up averaging out to small price changes over time, or that stocks with lower prices are more volatile, so even though they have large variances, the overall price change isn't as significant. Current Price and Volatility do have a negative correlation, so there is likely some truth behind that.

P/E Ratio looks to have very different distributions within different sectors, with certain sectors like Energy, Real Estate and IT having higher P/E ratios on average (as well as larger variances), while other sectors like Financials, Industrials, Utilities and Telecoms having much lower P/E ratio averages and variances.

One thing to note here: there looks to be some strange behavior on P/E ratios specifically within the Energy sector, where the median and 3rd quartile are exactly the same. Given that there are 30 Energy companies in this data set, that means that 8 or more companies have the exact same P/E ratio to the 6th decimal, which seems extremely unlikely. I want to explore this a bit further before I move on.

Data Preprocessing¶

  • Duplicate value check
  • Missing value treatment
  • Outlier check
  • Feature engineering (if needed)
  • Any other preprocessing steps (if needed)

We previously checked for duplicated and missing values and found nothing that needed to be cleaned up. For outliers, there are a significant number of outliers in many of the variables. However, they all appear to be legitimate data points so we need to keep them in the data set. Additionally, I'm choosing to not cap them at the whiskers for three reasons: First, the majority of outliers in most variables are skewed to the high side which represents a handful of typically very high value companies. Second, the variances in many of these variables are very different between sectors, so capping outliers could have a large impact on certain sectors and lead to them being more similar to other sectors than they truly are. Third, capping these outliers may have a significant impact on the clusters we create and could lead to misleading clusters and averages that don't truly represent the data.

K-means Clustering¶

In [33]:
kmeans_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [34]:
clusters = range(1, 15)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(kmeans_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(kmeans_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / kmeans_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)
plt.show()

cluster_list = range(2, 15)

None of these silhouette plots give us an ideal number of clusters, as there's continually a trend of one cluster having the high majority of data points and therefore skewing the average silhouette score, and then many of the other clusters have below average silhouette scores. Of these choices, however, it appears that 13 is the best option as it has the most even distribution of data points and is closest to having all clusters not be below the average score.

            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Comparing Dendrograms¶
In [54]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"] 

# Store results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# Subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(60, 60))

# plotting dendrogram and calculating cophenetic correlation for each method in the list of linkages
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(hier_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(hier_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

The dendrogram confirms that our best option is average linkage, which has a cophenetic correlation of .94. It also illustrates that the best number of clusters is 14, which we get from a line running through 6 on the y-axis. However, we can already see that we're going to have a similar situation as with the K-means clustering where we will have one cluster that has the majority of the Securities, with a few other much smaller clusters.

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

You compare several things, like:

  • Which clustering technique took less time for execution?
  • Which clustering technique gave you more distinct clusters, or are they the same?
  • How many observations are there in the similar clusters of both algorithms?
  • How many clusters are obtained as the appropriate number of clusters from both algorithms?

You can also mention any differences or similarities you obtained in the cluster profiles from both the clustering techniques.

The K-means clustering seemed to be easier for me, simply because I didn't need to analyze the dendrograms which took a while given the number of data points and multiple options which that provided.

I had more clusters in the hierarchical clustering, but also had the issue more severely of most data points being grouped into one individual cluster. This issue was still present in the k-means method, but not nearly as bad.

For k-means, the algorithm led to 13 clusters while hierarchical had 14. Both had a very uneven number of observations within clusters, with k-means ranging from 1 to over 200 while hierarchical ranged from 1 to 307. However, the 2nd largest cluster in hierarchical had just 7 observations, while in k-means there were 3 other clusters with over 25 observations.

Both algorithms seemed to be heavily influenced by the large outliers in the dataset, which led to either individual observation clusters, or else clusters with very few observations, while the high majority of observations were in a small number of clusters because they were much more similar compared to the outlier points. This overall seems to be a weakness of this approach.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

-

For a model recommendation, I recommend moving forward by using the clusters provided by the k-means algorithm. This model has observations more evenly distributed between the clusters, so we have a few denser groups that we can use to draw conclusions and gain insights, whereas the clusters from the hierarchical cluster algorithm are mostly made up of 1 or 2 data points, so all we can learn about the grouping is which data points are outliers on a given variable.

Based on the model, there are a few insights we can provide from this data set.

  • Cluster 5 is a very interesting grouping, made up of very well known and large companies mostly in the telecom and financial industry. Their net income and outstanding shares are extremely high on average, while their net cash flow and P/E ratio are very low compared to other clusters. This group could be described as large, mature companies that are very successful and valuable, but probably don't have as much potential for future growth.

  • Cluster 8 is also interesting, a group made up almost exclusively of energy companies. This group has one of the highest P/E ratios despite very negative net income and EPS. These stocks also appear to be very volatile and, though this may have just reflected changes in the energy market over the last two weeks, this group had the worst average price change at -$16.

  • Despite only being 3 companies, cluster 12 also stands out as very distinctive with an average P/E ratio over 5x higher than any other cluster and also had the best average price change at $21. This is all despite having the worst ROE and one of the lowest average EPS of any cluster. In contrast to cluster 5, these appear to be high potential companies that aren't yet driving the best financial performance but show a lot of belief from investors. Amazon and Netflix are in this cluster, which makes sense as they're two of the most popular tech stocks in the market.

  • Finally, I also think cluster 3 is interesting to analyze based on it having a strong P/E ratio, the highest P/B ratio of any cluster, and the best EPS outside of Cluster 9, which was only one observation. These are companies with very impressive financial performance that the market seems to believe will continue growing. Compared to cluster 5, these are smaller and younger companies, but may be a safe bet to continue growing.
